\'93Here\'92s a fearful honoured goddess in my home,\uc0\u8232 the one who saved me when I was in pain,\u8232 after my great fall, thanks to my mother,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0490\u8232 that shameless one, eager to conceal me,\u8232 because I was a cripple. At that time,\u8232 I would have suffered heartfelt agonies,\u8232 if Thetis and Eurynome, daughter\u8232 of circling Ocean stream, had not taken me\u8232 into their hearts. With those two, for nine years\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[400]\u8232 I made many lovely things\'97brooches,\u8232 spiral bracelets, earrings, necklaces\'97\u8232 inside their hollow cave. The Ocean stream\u8232 flowed round me, always with the roar of surf.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0500\u8232 No one else knew, neither god nor mortal man.\u8232 But Thetis and Eurynome\'97the ones\u8232 who rescued me\'97they knew.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://records.viu.ca/~johnstoi/homer/iliad18.htm#n1"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \strokec2 *}}\'a0And now Thetis\uc0\u8232 has come into my home. So I must give her\u8232 full recompense\'97fair-haired Thetis saved my life.\u8232 But Charis, show her now our hospitality.\u8232 I\'92ll put away my bellows and my tools.\'94\
Huge god Hephaestus got up from the anvil block\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[410]\uc0\u8232 with laboured breathing. He was lame, but his thin legs\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0510\u8232 moved quickly under him. He placed his bellows\u8232 far from the fire and collected all his work tools,\u8232 then stored them in a silver chest. With a sponge,\u8232 he wiped his face, both hands, thick neck, and hairy chest.\u8232 Then he pulled on a tunic and came limping out,\u8232 gripping a sturdy staff. At once he was helped along\u8232 by female servants made of gold, who moved to him.\u8232 They look like living servant girls, possessing minds,\u8232 hearts with intelligence, vocal chords, and strength.\u8232 They learned to work from the immortal gods.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0520\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[420]\u8232 These women served to give their master detailed help.\u8232 Hephaestus came limping up to Thetis and sat down\u8232 in a shining chair. Then, clasping her hand, he spoke:\
\'93Long-robed Thetis, why have you come here,\uc0\u8232 to our house, an honoured welcome guest?\u8232 To this point, you haven\'92t come here often.\u8232 But say what\'92s on your mind. My heart tells me\u8232 I shall do it, if I can accomplish it,\u8232 if it\'92s something that can be carried out.\'94\
Thetis answered him in tears:\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Oh, Hephaestus,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0530\uc0\u8232 is there any goddess on Olympus\u8232 who\'92s suffered so much painful sorrow\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[430]\u8232 in her heart to equal the unhappiness\u8232 that Zeus, son of Cronos, loads on me\u8232 more than any other god? Of all goddesses\u8232 living in the sea, he made me subject\u8232 to a mortal man, Peleus, son of Aeacus.\u8232 So I had to put up with a man in bed,\u8232 though much against my will. Now he lies there,\u8232 in his home, worn out by harsh old age.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0540\u8232 And I have still more pain. He gave me a son\u8232 to bear and raise as an outstanding warrior.\u8232 The boy grew up as quickly as a sapling.\u8232 Then, when I had reared him like a tree\u8232 in a fertile garden, I sent him off\u8232 in the beaked ships to fight at Ilion\u8232 against the Trojans. I\'92ll never welcome him\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[440]\u8232 returning home to the house of Peleus.\u8232 And while he still lives to glimpse the sunlight,\u8232 he lives in sorrow. When I visit him,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0550\u8232 I cannot help him. Achaea\'92s sons chose for him\u8232 as his prize a girl, whom great Agamemnon\u8232 seized right out of his arms. In grief for her,\u8232 his heart has pined away. Then the Trojans\u8232 penned Achaeans in by their ships\'92 sterns,\u8232 not letting them come out. The senior men\u8232 among the Argives pleaded with my son.\u8232 They promised splendid gifts. But he refused,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[450]\u8232 declining to protect them from disaster.\u8232 But then he sent Patroclus to the war,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0560\u8232 dressing him in his own armour, providing\u8232 a force of many men. They fought all day\u8232 around the Scaean Gates, and that very day\u8232 would have utterly destroyed the city,\u8232 if Apollo had not killed Menoetius\'92 son,\u8232 after he\'92d inflicted bloody carnage.\u8232 He killed him at the front, giving Hector\u8232 all the glory. That\'92s why I\'92ve come here now,\u8232 asking at your knees if you\'92d be willing\u8232 to give my son, who is fated to die soon,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0570\u8232 a shield, helmet, good leg armour fitted\u8232 with ankle clasps, and body armour, too.\u8232 His previous equipment was all taken\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[460]\u8232 when Trojans killed his loyal companion.\u8232 Now my son lies in the dust, heart filled with pain.\'94\
The famous crippled god then answered Thetis:\
\'93Cheer up. Don\'92t let these things afflict your heart.\uc0\u8232 I wish I could hide him from distressful death,\u8232 when his cruel fate arrives, as surely\u8232 as I know there\'92ll be fine armour for him\'97\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0580\u8232 such splendid armour that it will astound\u8232 all the many men who chance to see it.\'94\
With these words, Hephaestus left her there, going to start\uc0\u8232 his bellows. He directed them right at the fire,\u8232 then told them to start working. So the bellows,\u8232 twenty in all, started blowing on the crucibles,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[470]\u8232 each one emitting just the right amount of air,\u8232 sometimes blowing hard to help when he was busy,\u8232 sometimes gently, whatever way Hephaestus wished,\u8232 so his work could go ahead. He threw on the fire\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0590\u8232 enduring bronze and tin, precious gold and silver.\u8232 Next, he placed the great anvil on its block, took up\u8232 a massive hammer in one hand and in the other his tongs.\
The first thing he created was a huge and sturdy shield,\uc0\u8232 all wonderfully crafted. Around its outer edge,\u8232 he fixed a triple rim, glittering in the light,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[480]\u8232 attaching to it a silver carrying strap.\u8232 The shield had five layers. On the outer one,\u8232 with his great skill he fashioned many rich designs.\u8232 There he hammered out the earth, the heavens, the sea,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0600\u8232 the untiring sun, the moon at the full, along with\u8232 every constellation which crowns the heavens\'97\u8232 the Pleiades, the Hyades, mighty Orion,\u8232 and the Bear, which some people call the Wain,\u8232 always circling in the same position, watching Orion,\u8232 the only stars that never bathe in Ocean stream.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://records.viu.ca/~johnstoi/homer/iliad18.htm#n2"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \strokec2 *}}\
Then he created two splendid cities of mortal men.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[490]\uc0\u8232 In one, there were feasts and weddings. By the light\u8232 of blazing torches, people were leading the brides\u8232 out from their homes and through the town to loud music\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0610\u8232 of the bridal song. There were young lads dancing,\u8232 whirling to the constant tunes of flutes and lyres,\u8232 while all the women stood beside their doors, staring\u8232 in admiration.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Then the people gathered\uc0\u8232 in the assembly, for a dispute had taken place.\u8232 Two men were arguing about blood-money owed\u8232 for a murdered man. One claimed he\'92d paid in full,\u8232 setting out his case before the people, but the other\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[500]\u8232 was refusing any compensation. Both were keen\u8232 to receive the judgment from an arbitration.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0620\u8232 The crowd there cheered them on, some supporting one,\u8232 some the other, while heralds kept the throng controlled.\u8232 Meanwhile, elders were sitting there on polished stones\u8232 in the sacred circle, holding in their hands\u8232 the staffs they\'92d taken from the clear-voiced heralds.\u8232 With those they\'92d stand up there and render judgment,\u8232 each in his turn. In the centre lay two golden talents,\u8232 to be awarded to the one among them all\u8232 who would deliver the most righteous verdict.\
The second city was surrounded by two armies,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0630\uc0\u8232 soldiers with glittering weapons. They were discussing\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[510]\u8232 two alternatives, each one pleasing some of them\'97\u8232 whether to attack that city and plunder it,\u8232 or to accept as payment half of all the goods\u8232 contained in that fair town. But those under siege\u8232 who disagreed were arming for a secret ambush.\u8232 Their dear wives and children stood up on the walls\u8232 as a defence, along with those too old to fight.\u8232 The rest were leaving, led on by Pallas Athena\u8232 and Ares, both made of gold, dressed in golden clothes,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0640\u8232 large, beautiful, and armed\'97as is suitable for gods.\u8232 They stood out above the smaller people with them.\u8232 When the soldiers reached a spot which seemed all right\u8232 for ambush, a place beside a river where the cattle\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[520]\u8232 came to drink, they stopped there, covered in shining bronze.\u8232 Two scouts were stationed some distance from that army,\u8232 waiting to catch sight of sheep and short-horned cattle.\u8232 These soon appeared, followed by two herdsmen\u8232 playing their flutes and not anticipating any danger.\u8232 But those lying in ambush saw them and rushed out,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0650\u8232 quickly cutting off the herds of cattle and fine flocks\u8232 of white-fleeced sheep, killing the herdsmen with them.\u8232 When the besiegers sitting in their meeting place\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[530]\u8232 heard the great commotion coming from the cattle,\u8232 they quickly climbed up behind their prancing horses\u8232 and set out. They soon caught up with those attackers.\u8232 Then they organized themselves for battle and fought\u8232 along the river banks, men hitting one another\u8232 with bronze-tipped spears. Strife and Confusion joined the fight,\u8232 along with cruel Death, who seized one wounded man\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0660\u8232 while still alive and then another man without a wound,\u8232 while pulling the feet of one more corpse from the fight.\u8232 The clothes Death wore around her shoulders were dyed red\u8232 with human blood. They even joined the slaughter\u8232 as living mortals, fighting there and hauling off\u8232 the bodies of dead men which each of them had killed.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[540]\
